00:03:05.710 --> 00:03:10.190
The two biggest areas right
now of YouTube and Facebook,

00:03:10.190 --> 00:03:14.880
say they have over billions
of views every single day.

00:03:14.880 --> 00:03:19.290
Video content is very supreme
right now, when it comes

00:03:19.290 --> 00:03:25.350
to the social media
and on your websites.

00:03:25.350 --> 00:03:31.860
You see drone videos now
covering locations of businesses

00:03:31.860 --> 00:03:41.370
and many get to know us videos and
unboxing videos from influencers.

00:03:43.320 --> 00:03:45.310
Why do people love them?

00:03:45.310 --> 00:03:48.650
The joke of all the
cool kids are doing it.

00:03:48.650 --> 00:03:53.310
Then now there's this huge
wave of the influencer culture

00:03:53.310 --> 00:04:01.350
and so many people who go from
having this idea of they love makeup,

00:04:01.350 --> 00:04:06.120
so why not make videos of
learning how to put the makeup on

00:04:06.120 --> 00:04:11.270
and what products work for
them, what products don't work.

00:04:11.270 --> 00:04:17.080
Then video is great for boosting your
SEO to get the Google gods happy.

00:04:18.260 --> 00:04:23.320
Then there are relatively easy to
make, if you're only making videos,

00:04:24.950 --> 00:04:28.300
but when you're only making videos,
then they're not very accessible.

00:04:31.080 --> 00:04:35.110
When it comes to them not being
accessible or just other reasons,

00:04:35.110 --> 00:04:37.570
not everyone likes videos.

00:04:38.610 --> 00:04:42.580
I tend to actually be one of them
who don't really care for videos.

00:04:44.050 --> 00:04:48.180
My ADHD brain, even paying
attention to sitting in a movie

00:04:48.180 --> 00:04:52.610
without playing on my phone or
doing a little something else,

00:04:52.610 --> 00:04:56.360
I tend to lose interest in it.

00:04:56.360 --> 00:04:58.950
Right now,
just in the United States alone,

00:04:58.950 --> 00:05:03.840
13% of the population has
some sort of disability.

00:05:05.620 --> 00:05:08.809
With the disabilities of
being hearing impaired

00:05:08.809 --> 00:05:12.212
or visually impaired,
or even just cognitive differences

00:05:12.212 --> 00:05:18.460
can be a huge hurdle when it
comes to just watching videos.

00:05:18.460 --> 00:05:21.990
Some people dislike
being talked to.

00:05:23.230 --> 00:05:28.150
For a lot of the Facebook Live videos
when they first started talking,

00:05:28.150 --> 00:05:30.440
you would have a video of just
someone sitting in there with a phone

00:05:30.440 --> 00:05:34.550
like this just talking,
and it's almost like FaceTime,

00:05:34.550 --> 00:05:38.410
except for it's a one-sided talk.

00:05:38.410 --> 00:05:43.000
For those with me personally,
two minutes, not even two minutes in,

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:45.770
and I'm just like,
okay, this is boring.

00:05:45.770 --> 00:05:49.560
Then sometimes the content
can be very hard to comprehend

00:05:49.560 --> 00:05:53.670
if you have someone who is
talking really fast or talking

00:05:53.670 --> 00:05:57.730
with an accent that you're
not completely used to.

00:05:57.730 --> 00:06:00.560
There are those type of
videos, you see them,

00:06:00.560 --> 00:06:07.360
especially on like Facebook where
it's look what happened-type video

00:06:07.360 --> 00:06:10.670
and/or they're cooking
and they check the pot

00:06:10.670 --> 00:06:14.550
for three minutes instead of
just showing you the dish.

00:06:15.580 --> 00:06:20.680
Quite often,
even without a disability

00:06:20.680 --> 00:06:25.340
or different type of brain patterns,
you can get really impatient

00:06:25.340 --> 00:06:26.270
with that.

00:06:26.270 --> 00:06:29.870
Then also the quality of the video,
and with quality of the video,

00:06:29.870 --> 00:06:33.440
there's the sounds,
how clear people are talking.

00:06:33.440 --> 00:06:39.700
There is also like a bunch of
background noise and visual aspects

00:06:39.700 --> 00:06:42.090
of it because some can be fuzzy.

00:06:42.090 --> 00:06:46.460
Like if they're using their phone
to record and they've got a smudge

00:06:46.460 --> 00:06:50.620
on the lens, it can show
bad quality for the video,

00:06:50.620 --> 00:06:53.920
and then people might
not want to see it.

00:06:53.920 --> 00:06:58.620
In other non-accessible issues that
don't have to deal with like sound

00:06:58.620 --> 00:07:06.480
and vigil, is there's also all
the advertisements all the time.

00:07:06.480 --> 00:07:08.910
Right now,
if you're in the United States,

00:07:08.910 --> 00:07:14.210
we're getting ready next Tuesday
to have our midterm elections,

00:07:14.210 --> 00:07:20.500
and so with Facebook especially,
there's so many political ads.

00:07:22.010 --> 00:07:23.780
They're just all the time.

00:07:23.780 --> 00:07:28.710
You can watch a eight-minute
video with a girl talking

00:07:28.710 --> 00:07:35.980
about Egyptian history and there
could be seven different videos

00:07:35.980 --> 00:07:40.150
in that five-minute video ads
talking about the elections.

00:07:40.150 --> 00:07:44.430
Sometimes it's the same
ad over and over again.

00:07:44.430 --> 00:07:48.110
Then also on more YouTube
than the other ones,

00:07:48.110 --> 00:07:51.240
you have the subscriber pressure,
like, click here, please click here,

00:07:51.240 --> 00:07:53.240
please follow me here.

00:07:53.240 --> 00:07:59.840
Every so often, even if you were
able to keep attention to the video,

00:07:59.840 --> 00:08:03.300
the every, like a minute or
two saying, click this button,

00:08:03.300 --> 00:08:08.460
so prescribe here, don't miss
out, can break your thought on it.

00:08:08.460 --> 00:08:11.640
Then again, of just not
having a clear point to it.

00:08:11.640 --> 00:08:15.260
Then too much fluff can
make people lose interest.

00:08:17.090 --> 00:08:21.590
Even as adults and then
children also, there is a limit

00:08:21.590 --> 00:08:26.160
to how much cognitively
you can spend on something.

00:08:26.160 --> 00:08:32.770
Typically for a toddler to school
age, it's a minute per year.

00:08:32.770 --> 00:08:36.300
A two-year-old typically
only has about two minutes

00:08:36.300 --> 00:08:40.730
of attention they can spend
on any particular thing.

00:08:40.730 --> 00:08:45.600
Even as adults,
we tend to have that same repertoire

00:08:45.600 --> 00:08:49.162
where there's only so many minutes

00:08:49.162 --> 00:08:51.170
that something can
keep us interested,

00:08:51.170 --> 00:08:53.250
especially if we're
not interested in it.

00:08:55.150 --> 00:08:58.340
Then there's also different video
conflicts that can happen as well

00:08:58.340 --> 00:09:04.410
because there's no one size fits
all solution that comes for SEO,

00:09:04.410 --> 00:09:07.360
that comes for a website
builds, it comes from clothing,

00:09:07.360 --> 00:09:08.430
it comes from everything.

00:09:09.640 --> 00:09:13.410
We're just not a one size
fits all type of world.

00:09:15.770 --> 00:09:20.800
When it comes to accessibility,
we always think about the vision

00:09:20.800 --> 00:09:27.790
in audio accessibility,
but there's a broader area for that

00:09:27.790 --> 00:09:31.470
as well that needs to be
included when it comes to videos.

00:09:31.470 --> 00:09:34.974
It's your neurodivergent persons

00:09:34.974 --> 00:09:44.530
who might need more of grab you-type
attention to keep you interested.

00:09:44.530 --> 00:09:48.570
There's the ADHD brain, who if
you're talking about something

00:09:48.570 --> 00:09:52.720
in a very monotone voice and
you're just being kind of boring,

00:09:52.720 --> 00:09:57.040
that will also lose the
attention of the video.

00:09:57.040 --> 00:09:59.490
Auditory processing disorders.

00:09:59.490 --> 00:10:04.980
For me myself, I tend to read
lips to be able to understand more

00:10:04.980 --> 00:10:08.370
with the auditory processing
and that's where I will jump in

00:10:08.370 --> 00:10:13.180
and also say, I want to thank the
WordPress Accessibility Day team

00:10:13.180 --> 00:10:16.800
for having the ASL
interpreters on here.

00:10:16.800 --> 00:10:21.520
That is one thing I've always
been very appreciative of

00:10:21.520 --> 00:10:23.810
because I am a little
hard of hearing.

00:10:23.810 --> 00:10:28.400
I do read lips and then
also as a preschool teacher,

00:10:28.400 --> 00:10:30.700
before I started
working in WordPress,

00:10:30.700 --> 00:10:34.170
we would teach our younger
children the basic signs,

00:10:34.170 --> 00:10:38.310
like milk and more,
and please and thank you,

00:10:38.310 --> 00:10:42.960
to help them say their needs
before they could vocally do it.

00:10:42.960 --> 00:10:46.450
I have an 18 year old daughter
now, who is in college

00:10:46.450 --> 00:10:50.330
and uses a lot of the sign
language still for like,

00:10:50.330 --> 00:10:54.780
if you're at a loud
basketball game.

00:10:54.780 --> 00:10:57.750
You're trying to get the
person beside you's attention

00:10:57.750 --> 00:11:00.110
because you're wanting
to go get a drink.

00:11:00.110 --> 00:11:02.760
You're trying to yell, I want
water and they can't hear you,

00:11:02.760 --> 00:11:05.650
but if you tap on their shoulder
and then give the water sign,

00:11:06.980 --> 00:11:07.980
they know what you're doing.

00:11:09.320 --> 00:11:15.480
With auditory processing,
my daughter also has it as well

00:11:15.480 --> 00:11:20.220
and we have learned with sign and
lip reading, it helps us out a lot.

00:11:20.220 --> 00:11:23.330
Then also different
learning disabilities.

00:11:23.330 --> 00:11:28.850
There's a mixture of what can
help learn at different stages.

00:11:28.850 --> 00:11:35.700
You would not have a four-year-old
sit in front of just learning videos

00:11:35.700 --> 00:11:39.660
to learn how to tie their shoes.

00:11:41.510 --> 00:11:46.340
Then also,
at just different cognitive levels,

00:11:46.340 --> 00:11:51.960
you would want different aids
for helping to learn, which goes

00:11:51.960 --> 00:11:53.300
into that.

00:11:53.300 --> 00:11:58.070
There are many different learning
styles and not everyone can learn

00:11:58.070 --> 00:12:00.240
from just videos alone.

00:12:00.240 --> 00:12:03.900
Sometimes a person needs more
than one format to let it also in.

00:12:05.040 --> 00:12:09.820
Oftentimes, you'll have people
who are just vision learners

00:12:09.820 --> 00:12:14.320
who can do well with videos, but
then you have your auditory people

00:12:14.320 --> 00:12:18.060
who can play the video in the
background, just to hear the sounds

00:12:18.060 --> 00:12:20.950
of the people talking
and soak it all in.

00:12:20.950 --> 00:12:24.880
Then you have others who
wants to have a video,

00:12:24.880 --> 00:12:31.080
but also have a transcript of
it, so they can listen along to

00:12:31.080 --> 00:12:35.090
what is being done to be shown
what it is, and then go to try

00:12:35.090 --> 00:12:40.080
to do it with the
wording, also with it.

00:12:40.080 --> 00:12:47.530
Like for my at work, I train our
new project managers on the web team

00:12:47.530 --> 00:12:53.960
and we have a system that is,
tell it, show it, shadow it, do it.

00:12:53.960 --> 00:12:56.580
There's those four different
steps of doing everything

00:12:56.580 --> 00:12:59.270
and by the time you get
through that four step

00:12:59.270 --> 00:13:02.880
of doing it the first time,
you've absorbed all the information

00:13:02.880 --> 00:13:05.490
to do it,
which makes you more successful.

00:13:05.490 --> 00:13:10.490
When you're only having videos
on your website or sharing them

00:13:10.490 --> 00:13:14.060
in social media and you
don't have any text with it,

00:13:14.060 --> 00:13:18.440
it can make it very hard for
those people who do not learn well

00:13:18.440 --> 00:13:19.440
from videos.

00:13:21.920 --> 00:13:26.210
If you must use videos, then I will
admit I do like my videos as well

00:13:26.210 --> 00:13:30.280
on different things
that keep my attention.

00:13:30.280 --> 00:13:35.900
I love watching the videos
from WordFast and WordPress.tv

00:13:35.900 --> 00:13:40.240
from the talks of past.

00:13:42.050 --> 00:13:45.920
With those though, they have a
lot of options for accessibility

00:13:45.920 --> 00:13:47.680
to make them easier
for people to watch.

00:13:51.800 --> 00:13:52.880
Sorry, I had to grab a drink.

00:13:54.730 --> 00:14:00.530
All videos should first include
web friendly text and captions

00:14:00.530 --> 00:14:04.170
and transcripts and then PDFs
that allow for audio playback,

00:14:04.170 --> 00:14:05.820
when you share the
information with it.

00:14:06.870 --> 00:14:10.960
This is mostly for if you are
sharing them on your website.

00:14:10.960 --> 00:14:15.450
Like say, if I took the video
from this talk and posted it

00:14:15.450 --> 00:14:18.490
on Can't Speak Geek
for people to watch.

00:14:18.490 --> 00:14:23.210
I would want to have a copy of
the transcript attached to it,

00:14:24.420 --> 00:14:28.860
if I was to use the
logos from the sites

00:14:28.860 --> 00:14:32.720
to make sure they have
their alt text behind them

00:14:32.720 --> 00:14:35.550
and the font is very
friendly to read.

00:14:35.550 --> 00:14:40.190
Then also making
sure that the slides

00:14:40.190 --> 00:14:44.320
that I used also has web friendly
texts with spacing and easy to read.

00:14:45.570 --> 00:14:51.380
Then I am a huge fan when it comes
to captions on any type of videos.

00:14:51.380 --> 00:14:55.174
My husband and I both
use close captionings

00:14:55.175 --> 00:14:57.760
on our television for movies.

00:14:57.760 --> 00:15:01.420
It just makes it easier to be able
to understand what they're saying,

00:15:01.420 --> 00:15:04.840
especially when you
have videos and movies

00:15:04.840 --> 00:15:06.800
with a lot of background sounds.

00:15:07.820 --> 00:15:11.630
Then also for the PDFs that you
might attach with your videos,

00:15:11.630 --> 00:15:15.650
is to make sure that they allow
for the audio playback to happen.

00:15:18.800 --> 00:15:22.850
Then going back into a little
bit more of a deep dive of it,

00:15:22.850 --> 00:15:26.500
when it comes to the text in
your videos and on the pages

00:15:26.500 --> 00:15:30.120
that hold them, is make sure
you're choosing easy to read fonts,

00:15:30.120 --> 00:15:34.100
that there's large spacing
and that the text is also

00:15:34.100 --> 00:15:36.040
kind of a large font.

00:15:36.040 --> 00:15:43.130
Because the older you get, the more
harder it is to read smaller print.

00:15:43.130 --> 00:15:46.930
Then if you tend to need
bigger ones of the glasses,

00:15:48.670 --> 00:15:52.140
those also might make it harder
for you to read smaller fonts.

00:15:53.360 --> 00:16:01.000
Then also avoid animations in your
text because of with animations,

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:06.760
or like back in the late
'90s when the [inaudible]

00:16:06.760 --> 00:16:13.840
words were very popular and
they would have moving texts

00:16:13.840 --> 00:16:19.890
that's really hard for text readers
to grab onto and read in general.

00:16:21.320 --> 00:16:26.410
Then also keep in mind of your color
palettes for when you use color

00:16:26.410 --> 00:16:27.980
on text.

00:16:27.980 --> 00:16:32.420
Then for backgrounds, remember
for the contrast and highlights

00:16:33.470 --> 00:16:36.870
for important information,
so that it can stand out more

00:16:36.870 --> 00:16:37.870
for the reader.

00:16:39.080 --> 00:16:44.710
Also, when you're using the icons
and color contrasting in good fonts,

00:16:44.710 --> 00:16:47.830
it makes it so much easier
for your screen readers.

00:16:50.400 --> 00:16:55.690
Then with your videos, make sure
to always have the captions made

00:16:55.690 --> 00:16:56.770
during your live videos.

00:16:57.800 --> 00:17:00.460
It's really nice with
YouTube that they do have

00:17:00.460 --> 00:17:04.500
a speech recognition technology.

00:17:04.500 --> 00:17:09.500
However, with YouTube and
Vimeo and many of the others,

00:17:09.500 --> 00:17:14.390
it's a good start and you should
definitely go through and revise it

00:17:14.390 --> 00:17:16.820
to ensure that it is correct.

00:17:16.820 --> 00:17:21.510
The best way to also do that as
well, is have a script

00:17:21.510 --> 00:17:25.800
that you have written out
before you do your video

00:17:25.800 --> 00:17:28.950
that has everything that
is supposed to be said.

00:17:28.950 --> 00:17:32.140
Once the video's done and
you have to go back in

00:17:32.140 --> 00:17:38.190
and look at what the YouTube
speech recognition picked up,

00:17:38.190 --> 00:17:40.550
it makes it easier to
switch the words out.

00:17:41.800 --> 00:17:46.300
A lot of times when it
comes to the recognition,

00:17:46.300 --> 00:17:52.530
it picks up your normal words,
but if you tend to use slang

00:17:52.530 --> 00:17:59.130
or have a thicker accent,
or not enunciate very well,

00:17:59.130 --> 00:18:00.670
it won't pick it up as well.

00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:08.700
For us, people who are in the south
or even more southern than I am

00:18:08.700 --> 00:18:12.840
with the yous in the
y'all and words like that,

00:18:12.840 --> 00:18:16.710
it tends to not pick
them up as well.

00:18:16.710 --> 00:18:22.810
The also with the video captions,
they will not only pick up your words

00:18:22.810 --> 00:18:26.000
when done right, but it will
also pick up all the sounds

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:28.290
and turn them into text.

00:18:28.290 --> 00:18:32.580
If you're making a little commercial
type video of your business,

00:18:32.580 --> 00:18:36.220
then one of the things you
want is someone walking in

00:18:36.220 --> 00:18:39.940
through the door and you hear
the ding dong of the bell

00:18:39.940 --> 00:18:42.000
that it will pull it in there too.

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:48.220
When people who are having
auditory needs won't just hear

00:18:48.220 --> 00:18:51.330
the person talking,
but they'll be able to read

00:18:51.330 --> 00:18:54.080
that the doorbell dinged
and a person walked in,

00:18:54.080 --> 00:18:57.480
which makes it even more
engaging to the person

00:18:57.480 --> 00:18:59.740
