00:19:01.020 --> 00:19:03.440
Now there are two different
types of captioning.

00:19:03.440 --> 00:19:07.180
There's your closed captionings,
which those are encoded in

00:19:07.180 --> 00:19:10.280
with the video,
so it's all one file.

00:19:10.280 --> 00:19:14.490
Then you have the open
captions, which are a decoded

00:19:14.490 --> 00:19:18.540
from an existing subtitle
file, and that's usually made

00:19:18.540 --> 00:19:19.990
by a third party service.

00:19:21.460 --> 00:19:24.060
For that, it could be
whichever one you prefer,

00:19:24.060 --> 00:19:27.250
but typically code
captions work the best

00:19:27.250 --> 00:19:29.250
if you are doing all
of this manually.

00:19:31.930 --> 00:19:37.910
Then one of the things I love
the most about meeting videos

00:19:37.910 --> 00:19:43.680
and also training videos,
is to have a transcript to go along

00:19:43.680 --> 00:19:44.770
with it.

00:19:44.770 --> 00:19:50.680
A transcript is it takes all the
captions and and prints it out

00:19:50.680 --> 00:19:53.910
into a dialogue that
makes it searchable.

00:19:55.580 --> 00:19:59.330
For that,
I'm one who if I do have to listen

00:19:59.330 --> 00:20:04.730
to a little meeting video,
I will put it on like speed 1.5

00:20:04.730 --> 00:20:10.940
to 2 to go through it quickly,
or if it does come with a transcript,

00:20:10.940 --> 00:20:15.340
I more look at that and find where
I need, and then will go back

00:20:15.340 --> 00:20:19.720
to the video at that
particular time point.

00:20:19.720 --> 00:20:23.100
It helps because one, you don't
have to keep up with what's

00:20:23.100 --> 00:20:29.810
on the screen, especially in like
meeting videos, you want to skip

00:20:29.810 --> 00:20:34.320
