00:25:54.570 --> 00:25:59.080
Then there's some random other
thoughts for when it comes to sounds,

00:25:59.080 --> 00:26:01.180
to make them accessible.

00:26:01.180 --> 00:26:06.450
That's easy to do, is number
one, speak slow and clear

00:26:06.450 --> 00:26:08.950
and then also show
your speaker's face.

00:26:10.480 --> 00:26:16.790
Often, when it comes to
your auditory people,

00:26:16.790 --> 00:26:21.160
is when you have someone talking
like this and looking away,

00:26:21.160 --> 00:26:23.860
you can't really hear them.

00:26:25.260 --> 00:26:29.820
It's like the opposite
version of you driving

00:26:29.820 --> 00:26:32.960
and you turn the radio down to
make sure you don't get lost.

00:26:35.150 --> 00:26:39.660
Is that being able to see
it, to be able to hear it.

00:26:39.660 --> 00:26:43.470
Then block out white noise
when you're doing your videos.

00:26:43.470 --> 00:26:51.140
So if you are wanting to record
outside and there's a white

00:26:51.140 --> 00:26:54.460
outside humming or if
you're in an office

00:26:54.460 --> 00:27:00.410
and there's a bunch of just the not
really chatter towards distracting,

00:27:00.410 --> 00:27:04.600
but just your little noises
rubbing back and forth.

00:27:04.600 --> 00:27:07.440
Then try to avoid
using filler words.

00:27:07.440 --> 00:27:12.180
This is the one thing I try
the most on as a speaker,

00:27:12.180 --> 00:27:14.770
but still sometimes
have issues with.

00:27:14.770 --> 00:27:18.820
The filler words are your
ums, your uhs, your huhs, uh

00:27:19.970 --> 00:27:22.560
and they are fillers to save area.

00:27:24.570 --> 00:27:32.980
Also, have a narrator to help you
with the background audio in it.

00:27:32.980 --> 00:27:35.230
Have a non-distracting background.

00:27:35.230 --> 00:27:38.430
How many times especially back in

00:27:38.430 --> 00:27:42.880
when more local radio stations
were bigger than they are now,

00:27:42.880 --> 00:27:47.880
and they would do the live radio
events and you would have the,

00:27:47.880 --> 00:27:51.140
hi, my name is Michelle
Jones and I'm coming to you

00:27:51.140 --> 00:27:52.920
from our local grocery store.

00:27:54.790 --> 00:27:58.910
Those were just audio,
but even in videos now

00:27:58.910 --> 00:28:02.210
where you have the person
talking at the grocery store,

00:28:02.210 --> 00:28:05.670
but you have all the noise of
the carts coming back and forth

00:28:05.670 --> 00:28:10.520
and maybe a child screaming in the
background or a husband talking

00:28:10.520 --> 00:28:14.180
to the wife, to where you're hearing
all of these surrounding noises

00:28:14.180 --> 00:28:17.190
around that one person
trying to talk about being

00:28:17.190 --> 00:28:18.970
at the grocery store.

00:28:18.970 --> 00:28:25.240
You have a hard time trying to
stay pinpointed on the lead person

00:28:25.240 --> 00:28:27.840
because of all of that
distracting background noise.

00:28:30.140 --> 00:28:35.480
Then some random other thoughts
to do for your visuals, is again,

00:28:35.480 --> 00:28:38.940
nothing blinking
flashing or strobing.

00:28:38.940 --> 00:28:43.030
This is big for anyone
who has epilepsy,

00:28:43.030 --> 00:28:50.020
but it's also very beneficial
for if someone has vision issues

00:28:50.020 --> 00:28:55.340
and where it is their
sensitive to light and anything

00:28:55.340 --> 00:28:58.620
like real bright flashing, especially
if you're the type of person

00:28:58.620 --> 00:29:02.830
to use the dark views
on your monitors.

00:29:02.830 --> 00:29:05.240
If you have a dark view
and you start a page

00:29:05.240 --> 00:29:10.060
and all of a sudden there's this
glowing blinking thing coming at you,

00:29:10.060 --> 00:29:13.230
it can take your eyes a minute to
adjust and it can really hurt them

00:29:13.230 --> 00:29:15.110
if you have very sensitive eyes.

00:29:16.650 --> 00:29:20.020
Then also with the
flashing and strobing,

00:29:20.020 --> 00:29:22.560
that can be just very
distractive as well

00:29:22.560 --> 00:29:28.680
and the audio cannot pick those up.

00:29:28.680 --> 00:29:32.270
Then another thing that is
really thought of quite often,

00:29:32.270 --> 00:29:34.420
is the smooth
movements of a camera.

00:29:35.560 --> 00:29:41.390
If you watch like the Blair Witch
movies, where they're running

00:29:41.390 --> 00:29:45.210
through the woods and the videos
are just jumping everywhere,

00:29:45.210 --> 00:29:47.000
it's hard to keep
attention with it.

00:29:47.000 --> 00:29:50.810
It's hard to really convey
what's going on in the video

00:29:50.810 --> 00:29:53.120
because of the movement.

00:29:53.120 --> 00:29:55.920
Also, it could just
create motion sickness

00:29:55.920 --> 00:29:59.210
for some people watching it,
if they have a sensitive stomach.

00:30:00.550 --> 00:30:04.450
The smoother you can make
the movements of the camera

00:30:04.450 --> 00:30:09.990
and the ease of use of just
going through everything,

00:30:09.990 --> 00:30:12.200
it makes it a lot easier.

00:30:12.200 --> 00:30:15.700
Then remember your color contrasting
when it comes to making videos,

00:30:15.700 --> 00:30:18.380
especially if you're
using a green screen.

00:30:20.370 --> 00:30:23.820
For example,
